[{"category":"section","location":"phases/#Phase-functions","page":"Phase functions","text":"","title":"Phase functions"},{"category":"type","location":"phases/#NumericalSteepestDescent.PolynomialPhase","page":"Phase functions","text":"struct PolynomialPhase\n\nAssumes g(z) = ∑ αj z^j, with αJ ≠ 0 and J≥2\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"NumericalSteepestDescent.PolynomialPhase"},{"category":"type","location":"phases/#NumericalSteepestDescent.LinearPhase","page":"Phase functions","text":"struct LinearPhase\n\nAssumes that g(z) = z\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"NumericalSteepestDescent.LinearPhase"},{"category":"type","location":"phases/#NumericalSteepestDescent.SquareRootPhase","page":"Phase functions","text":"Struct SquareRootPhase\n\ng(z) = √(z^2+a^2) + b*z where a>0 and b in (-1,1).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"NumericalSteepestDescent.SquareRootPhase"},{"category":"type","location":"phases/#NumericalSteepestDescent.RationalPhase","page":"Phase functions","text":"Struct for rational phase function\n\ng(z) = ∑ αj z^j + ∑∑ α_(p,k) / (z-zp)^k, where zp are poles of the function and α_(p,k) \nare the coefficients of the singular part associated with pole p.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"NumericalSteepestDescent.RationalPhase"},{"category":"section","location":"#NumericalSteepestDescent.jl","page":"Home","text":"NumericalSteepestDescent.jl is a Julia package for the numerical evaluation of highly oscillatory integrals. The aim is to efficiently evaluate integrals of the form\n\nI = int_a^b f(z)exp(mathrmiomega g(z)) mathrmdz\n\nwhere g is phase, f is amplitude, omega0 is a frequency parameter, and the endpoints a and b may be finite or infinite. Further, it is assumed that I is a convergent integral and that f(z) grows sub-exponentially as ztoinfty.\n\nThis package is an automatic implementation of a regularised numerical steepest descent method, but it can be used without a deep understanding of the underlying mathematics.\n\nFor a a full explanation of the underlying mathematics, the interested reader is referred to [Gibbs, Hewett, Huybrechs, '24].\n\nThe simplest use case is integrating with a polynomial phase function.\n\nusing NumericalSteepestDescent\n\n# Define the phase: g(z) = 3 + 5z + 6z² + 2z³\nPhase = PolynomialPhase([3, 5, 6, 2])\n\n# Integration endpoints\na, b = -1.0, 1.0\n\n# Amplitude function (can be any function)\nf(z) = 1.0  # constant amplitude\n\n# Frequency parameter\nω = 1000.0\n\n# Compute the integral\nresult = nsd([a, b], f, Phase, ω)\n\nFor the case of arbitrary polynomial phase, there is also a MATLAB implementation available. See [PathFinder, '25]. ","title":"NumericalSteepestDescent.jl"},{"category":"function","location":"#NumericalSteepestDescent.nsd","page":"Home","text":"Compute the oscillatory integral with\n    - finite endpoints (a,b), or infinite endpoints with angle (a,b) if specified\n    - amplitude function f\n    - phase function G\n    - frequency ω\nReturns the value and a vector of figures\n\nγ0 is assumed as the union of straight lines connecting given points\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"NumericalSteepestDescent.nsd"}]
